[{"name":"Ferrers","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: locative name from Ferrières-Saint-Hilaire (Eure) and Ferrières (Manche)."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferris","meanings":["Irish and Scottish: shortened Anglicized form of Irish <b>Ó Fearghuis</b> or <b>Ó Fearghasa</b> ‘descendant of <i>Fearghus</i>’, or from the Scottish-Gaelic form of this personal name, <i>Fearghus</i> (see   Fergus  ).","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Ferrières-Saint-Hilaire, Eure and Ferrières, La Manche in Normandy, France."]},{"name":"Ferridge","meanings":["English: unexplained; possibly a form of  <i>Ferris</i> and therefore a variant of   Ferrers  ."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":11,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Joan Ferrers was born in 1248, in Devon, England. She married William Bonville about 1259, in Devon, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. She died in 1268, in her hometown, at the age of 20."},"et":{"1248–1268":"1248–1268","1230–1268":"1230–1268","1260–1295":"1260–1295","1265–1325":"1265–1325","1267–Male":"1267–Surnud","1248":"1248","1259":"1259","1325":"1325","1268":"1268","1267":"1267","about 1259":"umbes 1259","Abt 1265":"umbes 1265","1265":"1265","1230":"1230","1295":"1295","1260":"1260","Wiscomb, Devon, England":"Devon, England","Wiscombe Park, Devon, England":"Wiscombe Park, Devon, England","Devonshire, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Devon, Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fi":{"1248–1268":"1248–1268","1230–1268":"1230–1268","1260–1295":"1260–1295","1265–1325":"1265–1325","1267–Male":"1267–Kuollut","1248":"1248","1259":"1259","1325":"1325","1268":"1268","1267":"1267","about 1259":"noin 1259","Abt 1265":"noin 1265","1265":"1265","1230":"1230